window.__XF_SKILL_PACKS__=window.__XF_SKILL_PACKS__||{};window.__XF_SKILL_PACKS__["wedding-event-planning-toolkit-pack"]={"id": "wedding-event-planning-toolkit-pack", "skills": [{"id": "budget-tracker-narrative", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'budget-tracker-narrative' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/budget-tracker-narrative/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/budget-tracker-narrative/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/budget-tracker-narrative/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/budget-tracker-narrative/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/budget-tracker-narrative/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: budget-tracker-narrative\ndescription: >\n  Turns a raw wedding/event budget spreadsheet into a plain-language narrative of where the money actually stands - overspend risk, categories trending over, and what to do about it. Triggers: \"tell me in plain English where our wedding budget stands\", \"narrate this event budget for the client\", /budget-tracker-narrative.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: medium\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /budget-tracker-narrative\n\nConverts a raw budget spreadsheet (category, estimated, actual, paid-so-far) into a plain-language narrative that says clearly where the money stands, which categories are trending over, and what specifically to do about it.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA couple or event planner has a budget spreadsheet with numbers in it but needs someone to actually read it and say what it means in plain terms - are we on track, which categories are the problem, and what's the real total risk - rather than staring at a grid of numbers.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- The raw budget data: category, original estimate, actual/quoted cost, amount paid so far, amount still due\n- Total budget ceiling, if one was set\n- Event date, since how much runway is left affects how urgent a course-correction needs to be\n- Any category the couple/client has already flagged as flexible versus non-negotiable\n\n## Safety\n\nPropose before acting: this narrative is for review and decision-making by the couple/client - any suggested cut, reallocation, or vendor renegotiation should be confirmed with them before anyone acts on it or contacts a vendor.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Calculate the actual current total (sum of actual/quoted costs across all categories) against the budget ceiling, and state the gap in plain dollar terms and percentage - over or under - as the very first thing in the narrative.\n2. Identify which specific categories are running over their original estimate and by how much, ranked by dollar amount over (not percentage over), since a small-percentage overage in a huge category can matter more than a huge-percentage overage in a tiny one.\n3. Separate what's already paid/locked in (can't be changed without cancellation costs) from what's still a quote or estimate (still negotiable or substitutable) - the narrative's \"what to do\" advice only makes sense against the still-flexible portion.\n4. Cross-reference overage categories against any categories the couple/client already flagged as flexible versus non-negotiable, and frame reallocation suggestions only around the flexible ones.\n5. State the amount still due and when, separate from the overall total, since cash-flow timing (what's due before the event versus after) matters as much as the grand total for near-term decisions.\n6. If the total is trending over budget, propose two or three concrete, specific reallocation or cut options (not vague \"consider trimming costs\") grounded in the actual flexible categories identified.\n7. If the budget is on track or under, say so plainly and briefly rather than manufacturing concern - a clean narrative should feel proportionate to the actual risk level.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nBUDGET NARRATIVE - [Event] - as of [date]\n\nBOTTOM LINE: [Over/under/on track] by $[X] ([Y]% of total budget of $[Z])\n\nWHERE THE OVERAGE IS COMING FROM (ranked by $ amount)\n1. [Category]: est. $X → actual $Y (+$Z over)\n2. [Category]: ...\n\nLOCKED IN vs. STILL FLEXIBLE\n- Locked in (paid/contracted): $[X]\n- Still a quote/estimate (negotiable): $[X]\n\nSTILL DUE\n- $[X] due by [date], $[X] due by [date]\n\nIF OVER BUDGET - OPTIONS (grounded in flexible categories only)\n- Option 1: [specific reallocation/cut] - saves ~$[X]\n- Option 2: [specific reallocation/cut] - saves ~$[X]\n\n[If on track/under budget: one plain confirming sentence, no manufactured concern]\n```\n\n## Do\n- Lead with the bottom-line gap in plain dollar and percentage terms.\n- Rank overage categories by dollar amount, not percentage, since that reflects real impact.\n- Ground every cut/reallocation suggestion in categories already marked flexible.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't propose cuts to categories the couple/client already marked non-negotiable.\n- Don't manufacture urgency if the budget is actually on track - match tone to real risk.\n- Don't blend \"locked in\" and \"still a quote\" spend into one number when discussing what can still change.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Bottom-line gap appears first, in both dollars and percentage\n- [ ] Locked-in and still-flexible spend are clearly separated\n- [ ] Any suggested cut respects previously stated non-negotiable categories\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /budget-tracker-narrative or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: budget-tracker-narrative\ndescription: >\n  Turns a raw wedding/event budget spreadsheet into a plain-language narrative of where the money actually stands - overspend risk, categories trending over, and what to do about it. Triggers: \"tell me in plain English where our wedding budget stands\", \"narrate this event budget for the client\", /budget-tracker-narrative.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: monthly\n  risk: medium\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /budget-tracker-narrative\n\nConverts a raw budget spreadsheet (category, estimated, actual, paid-so-far) into a plain-language narrative that says clearly where the money stands, which categories are trending over, and what specifically to do about it.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA couple or event planner has a budget spreadsheet with numbers in it but needs someone to actually read it and say what it means in plain terms - are we on track, which categories are the problem, and what's the real total risk - rather than staring at a grid of numbers.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- The raw budget data: category, original estimate, actual/quoted cost, amount paid so far, amount still due\n- Total budget ceiling, if one was set\n- Event date, since how much runway is left affects how urgent a course-correction needs to be\n- Any category the couple/client has already flagged as flexible versus non-negotiable\n\n## Safety\n\nPropose before acting: this narrative is for review and decision-making by the couple/client - any suggested cut, reallocation, or vendor renegotiation should be confirmed with them before anyone acts on it or contacts a vendor.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Calculate the actual current total (sum of actual/quoted costs across all categories) against the budget ceiling, and state the gap in plain dollar terms and percentage - over or under - as the very first thing in the narrative.\n2. Identify which specific categories are running over their original estimate and by how much, ranked by dollar amount over (not percentage over), since a small-percentage overage in a huge category can matter more than a huge-percentage overage in a tiny one.\n3. Separate what's already paid/locked in (can't be changed without cancellation costs) from what's still a quote or estimate (still negotiable or substitutable) - the narrative's \"what to do\" advice only makes sense against the still-flexible portion.\n4. Cross-reference overage categories against any categories the couple/client already flagged as flexible versus non-negotiable, and frame reallocation suggestions only around the flexible ones.\n5. State the amount still due and when, separate from the overall total, since cash-flow timing (what's due before the event versus after) matters as much as the grand total for near-term decisions.\n6. If the total is trending over budget, propose two or three concrete, specific reallocation or cut options (not vague \"consider trimming costs\") grounded in the actual flexible categories identified.\n7. If the budget is on track or under, say so plainly and briefly rather than manufacturing concern - a clean narrative should feel proportionate to the actual risk level.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nBUDGET NARRATIVE - [Event] - as of [date]\n\nBOTTOM LINE: [Over/under/on track] by $[X] ([Y]% of total budget of $[Z])\n\nWHERE THE OVERAGE IS COMING FROM (ranked by $ amount)\n1. [Category]: est. $X → actual $Y (+$Z over)\n2. [Category]: ...\n\nLOCKED IN vs. STILL FLEXIBLE\n- Locked in (paid/contracted): $[X]\n- Still a quote/estimate (negotiable): $[X]\n\nSTILL DUE\n- $[X] due by [date], $[X] due by [date]\n\nIF OVER BUDGET - OPTIONS (grounded in flexible categories only)\n- Option 1: [specific reallocation/cut] - saves ~$[X]\n- Option 2: [specific reallocation/cut] - saves ~$[X]\n\n[If on track/under budget: one plain confirming sentence, no manufactured concern]\n```\n\n## Do\n- Lead with the bottom-line gap in plain dollar and percentage terms.\n- Rank overage categories by dollar amount, not percentage, since that reflects real impact.\n- Ground every cut/reallocation suggestion in categories already marked flexible.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't propose cuts to categories the couple/client already marked non-negotiable.\n- Don't manufacture urgency if the budget is actually on track - match tone to real risk.\n- Don't blend \"locked in\" and \"still a quote\" spend into one number when discussing what can still change.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Bottom-line gap appears first, in both dollars and percentage\n- [ ] Locked-in and still-flexible spend are clearly separated\n- [ ] Any suggested cut respects previously stated non-negotiable categories\n"}, {"id": "day-of-timeline-builder", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'day-of-timeline-builder' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/day-of-timeline-builder/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/day-of-timeline-builder/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/day-of-timeline-builder/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/day-of-timeline-builder/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/day-of-timeline-builder/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: day-of-timeline-builder\ndescription: >\n  Builds a minute-by-minute wedding or event day-of timeline that accounts for real buffer time and hands off clear cues to every vendor and key person involved. Triggers: \"build the day-of timeline for the wedding\", \"put together a run of show for the reception\", /day-of-timeline-builder.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: medium\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /day-of-timeline-builder\n\nBuilds a minute-by-minute day-of timeline with realistic buffers between transitions and a distribution-ready cue sheet naming exactly who needs to do what and when.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nAn event (wedding, milestone party, corporate event) has a set of major moments already decided (ceremony time, dinner, speeches, first dance) and needs those moments translated into an actual sequenced schedule with transition time, vendor call times, and clear ownership - the document that actually runs the day.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- Ceremony/event start time and any other fixed-time anchors already set (venue access time, vendor arrival windows, transportation pickup times)\n- Full list of planned moments/segments (getting ready, ceremony, cocktail hour, entrances, dinner, toasts, first dance, cake, open dancing, send-off)\n- Vendor list and their known call times or setup needs, if known\n- Guest count and venue layout details that affect transition time (e.g., distance between ceremony and reception space)\n\n## Safety\n\n- Propose before acting: this is a working draft for review by the couple/client and vendors - confirm it with all key parties before it's treated as final and distributed.\n- Never distribute a timeline as final without an explicit confirmation step from the couple/client.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Place every genuinely fixed-time commitment on the timeline first (ceremony start, venue access/vendor load-in windows, transportation) as anchors that can't move.\n2. Work backward from the ceremony start to build the getting-ready sequence (hair/makeup, photos, transportation) with realistic time per person/group, not an idealized best-case duration.\n3. Work forward from the ceremony through the reception, sequencing each planned moment (cocktail hour, entrances, dinner service, toasts, cake, dances, open dancing, send-off) with a realistic duration for each based on guest count and venue logistics.\n4. Insert explicit buffer time between every transition (ceremony to cocktail hour, dinner to toasts, etc.) - 10-15 minutes minimum for larger or more logistically complex transitions - since back-to-back scheduling with zero slack is the single most common cause of a timeline falling apart in real time.\n5. Assign each timeline entry an owner (who needs to cue it, who needs to be ready, which vendor is responsible) so the document functions as an operational cue sheet, not just a schedule for reference.\n6. Flag the tightest transition in the whole day (usually ceremony-to-photos-to-reception) and note a specific contingency if it runs long (what gets shortened or cut first) rather than letting a delay cascade through the rest of the night unplanned.\n7. Produce a vendor-specific extract for each vendor showing only their own call times and cues, so the full timeline doesn't need to be parsed by everyone - each vendor gets exactly what applies to them.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nDAY-OF TIMELINE - [Event] - [date]\n\n| Time | Duration | Segment | Location | Owner/Cue |\n|------|----------|---------|----------|-----------|\n| ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |\n\nBUFFER NOTES\n- [Transition] has [X] min buffer built in because [reason]\n\nTIGHTEST POINT IN THE DAY\n[Transition] - contingency if running late: [what gets shortened/cut first]\n\nVENDOR EXTRACTS\n[Vendor name] - your call times and cues only:\n| Time | What's needed from you |\n|------|------------------------|\n(repeat per vendor)\n\nCONFIRMATION NEEDED FROM: [couple/client] before distribution\n```\n\n## Do\n- Build in real buffer time between every transition, not just at the start or end of the day.\n- Identify the single tightest point in the day and give it an explicit contingency plan.\n- Produce vendor-specific extracts so each vendor only sees what applies to them.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't schedule transitions back-to-back with zero slack - that's the most common real-world failure point.\n- Don't distribute the timeline as final without explicit confirmation from the couple/client first.\n- Don't build getting-ready or dinner-service durations on best-case assumptions - use realistic timing for the actual guest count and vendor setup involved.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Every transition has explicit buffer time, not back-to-back zero-slack scheduling\n- [ ] The tightest point in the day has a named contingency plan\n- [ ] A confirmation gate appears before the timeline is treated as final/distributed\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /day-of-timeline-builder or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: day-of-timeline-builder\ndescription: >\n  Builds a minute-by-minute wedding or event day-of timeline that accounts for real buffer time and hands off clear cues to every vendor and key person involved. Triggers: \"build the day-of timeline for the wedding\", \"put together a run of show for the reception\", /day-of-timeline-builder.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: medium\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /day-of-timeline-builder\n\nBuilds a minute-by-minute day-of timeline with realistic buffers between transitions and a distribution-ready cue sheet naming exactly who needs to do what and when.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nAn event (wedding, milestone party, corporate event) has a set of major moments already decided (ceremony time, dinner, speeches, first dance) and needs those moments translated into an actual sequenced schedule with transition time, vendor call times, and clear ownership - the document that actually runs the day.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- Ceremony/event start time and any other fixed-time anchors already set (venue access time, vendor arrival windows, transportation pickup times)\n- Full list of planned moments/segments (getting ready, ceremony, cocktail hour, entrances, dinner, toasts, first dance, cake, open dancing, send-off)\n- Vendor list and their known call times or setup needs, if known\n- Guest count and venue layout details that affect transition time (e.g., distance between ceremony and reception space)\n\n## Safety\n\n- Propose before acting: this is a working draft for review by the couple/client and vendors - confirm it with all key parties before it's treated as final and distributed.\n- Never distribute a timeline as final without an explicit confirmation step from the couple/client.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Place every genuinely fixed-time commitment on the timeline first (ceremony start, venue access/vendor load-in windows, transportation) as anchors that can't move.\n2. Work backward from the ceremony start to build the getting-ready sequence (hair/makeup, photos, transportation) with realistic time per person/group, not an idealized best-case duration.\n3. Work forward from the ceremony through the reception, sequencing each planned moment (cocktail hour, entrances, dinner service, toasts, cake, dances, open dancing, send-off) with a realistic duration for each based on guest count and venue logistics.\n4. Insert explicit buffer time between every transition (ceremony to cocktail hour, dinner to toasts, etc.) - 10-15 minutes minimum for larger or more logistically complex transitions - since back-to-back scheduling with zero slack is the single most common cause of a timeline falling apart in real time.\n5. Assign each timeline entry an owner (who needs to cue it, who needs to be ready, which vendor is responsible) so the document functions as an operational cue sheet, not just a schedule for reference.\n6. Flag the tightest transition in the whole day (usually ceremony-to-photos-to-reception) and note a specific contingency if it runs long (what gets shortened or cut first) rather than letting a delay cascade through the rest of the night unplanned.\n7. Produce a vendor-specific extract for each vendor showing only their own call times and cues, so the full timeline doesn't need to be parsed by everyone - each vendor gets exactly what applies to them.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nDAY-OF TIMELINE - [Event] - [date]\n\n| Time | Duration | Segment | Location | Owner/Cue |\n|------|----------|---------|----------|-----------|\n| ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |\n\nBUFFER NOTES\n- [Transition] has [X] min buffer built in because [reason]\n\nTIGHTEST POINT IN THE DAY\n[Transition] - contingency if running late: [what gets shortened/cut first]\n\nVENDOR EXTRACTS\n[Vendor name] - your call times and cues only:\n| Time | What's needed from you |\n|------|------------------------|\n(repeat per vendor)\n\nCONFIRMATION NEEDED FROM: [couple/client] before distribution\n```\n\n## Do\n- Build in real buffer time between every transition, not just at the start or end of the day.\n- Identify the single tightest point in the day and give it an explicit contingency plan.\n- Produce vendor-specific extracts so each vendor only sees what applies to them.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't schedule transitions back-to-back with zero slack - that's the most common real-world failure point.\n- Don't distribute the timeline as final without explicit confirmation from the couple/client first.\n- Don't build getting-ready or dinner-service durations on best-case assumptions - use realistic timing for the actual guest count and vendor setup involved.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Every transition has explicit buffer time, not back-to-back zero-slack scheduling\n- [ ] The tightest point in the day has a named contingency plan\n- [ ] A confirmation gate appears before the timeline is treated as final/distributed\n"}, {"id": "guest-communication-templates", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'guest-communication-templates' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/guest-communication-templates/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/guest-communication-templates/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/guest-communication-templates/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/guest-communication-templates/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/guest-communication-templates/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: guest-communication-templates\ndescription: >\n  Drafts a set of guest-facing wedding/event messages (save-the-date follow-up, logistics email, dietary/accessibility ask, day-of reminders) matched to the couple's actual tone and event details. Triggers: \"write the email telling guests about the hotel block\", \"draft a message asking about dietary restrictions\", /guest-communication-templates.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /guest-communication-templates\n\nDrafts the specific guest-facing message needed at this stage of planning - logistics update, dietary/accessibility request, day-of reminder - matched to the actual event details and the couple's tone, not a generic wedding-template voice.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA specific guest communication needs to go out - informing guests of hotel blocks and transportation, collecting dietary/accessibility needs, sending day-of arrival reminders, or any other point in the planning timeline where guests need real information, not vague warmth.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- What this specific message needs to communicate or collect (the actual content/logistics)\n- Couple's/host's tone preference (formal, casual, playful) and whether it's from the couple directly or the planner on their behalf\n- Response needed from guests, if any, and by when\n- Channel (email, text, wedding website update, printed insert) since format constraints differ\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Identify the single core piece of information or request this message needs to deliver, and lead with it - don't bury the actual logistics under extended warm preamble.\n2. Match the tone to what the couple/host specified - a casual couple's voice reads very differently from a formal invitation-style voice, and a generic \"wedding template\" tone undersells either.\n3. If information is being requested from guests (dietary restrictions, plus-one details, accessibility needs), phrase the ask specifically and make responding as low-friction as possible (a direct reply, a simple form link, a yes/no format) rather than an open-ended question that invites rambling responses that are hard to compile later.\n4. If this is a logistics message (transportation, hotel block, weather contingency, parking), give the concrete detail plainly - address, time, deadline, cost - not a vague pointer to \"more info coming soon.\"\n5. State clearly whether a response is needed and the deadline, if applicable, so guests know whether to act or just note the information.\n6. Match the message length to the channel - a text/day-of reminder should be a few lines; an email logistics update can carry more detail; a website update can be the most comprehensive version.\n7. If this message is sensitive (e.g., a no-kids policy, an adults-only reception, a request not to post photos, a cash-only bar), phrase it plainly and kindly without over-apologizing or making it sound negotiable if it isn't.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\n[Message type]: [purpose]\nChannel: [email/text/website/insert]\nTone: [as specified]\n\nSubject (if email): [subject line]\n\n[Message body - core info first, warmth wrapped around it, response instructions if needed, deadline if applicable]\n\nResponse needed: [Yes/No] - by [date] - via [method]\n```\n\n## Do\n- Lead with the actual logistics/ask, wrapped in warmth rather than buried under it.\n- Make any requested guest response low-friction and easy to compile (specific format, not open-ended).\n- Match message length and formality to the actual channel it's going out on.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't default to a generic \"wedding template\" voice if the couple specified a different tone.\n- Don't phrase sensitive policies (no kids, cash bar, no photos) apologetically in a way that makes them sound negotiable if they aren't.\n- Don't leave a response deadline implicit - state it explicitly if a reply is needed.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] The core logistics/ask appears early, not buried under preamble\n- [ ] Any requested guest response has a clear format and deadline\n- [ ] Tone matches what the couple/host specified, not a generic default\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /guest-communication-templates or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: guest-communication-templates\ndescription: >\n  Drafts a set of guest-facing wedding/event messages (save-the-date follow-up, logistics email, dietary/accessibility ask, day-of reminders) matched to the couple's actual tone and event details. Triggers: \"write the email telling guests about the hotel block\", \"draft a message asking about dietary restrictions\", /guest-communication-templates.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /guest-communication-templates\n\nDrafts the specific guest-facing message needed at this stage of planning - logistics update, dietary/accessibility request, day-of reminder - matched to the actual event details and the couple's tone, not a generic wedding-template voice.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA specific guest communication needs to go out - informing guests of hotel blocks and transportation, collecting dietary/accessibility needs, sending day-of arrival reminders, or any other point in the planning timeline where guests need real information, not vague warmth.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- What this specific message needs to communicate or collect (the actual content/logistics)\n- Couple's/host's tone preference (formal, casual, playful) and whether it's from the couple directly or the planner on their behalf\n- Response needed from guests, if any, and by when\n- Channel (email, text, wedding website update, printed insert) since format constraints differ\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Identify the single core piece of information or request this message needs to deliver, and lead with it - don't bury the actual logistics under extended warm preamble.\n2. Match the tone to what the couple/host specified - a casual couple's voice reads very differently from a formal invitation-style voice, and a generic \"wedding template\" tone undersells either.\n3. If information is being requested from guests (dietary restrictions, plus-one details, accessibility needs), phrase the ask specifically and make responding as low-friction as possible (a direct reply, a simple form link, a yes/no format) rather than an open-ended question that invites rambling responses that are hard to compile later.\n4. If this is a logistics message (transportation, hotel block, weather contingency, parking), give the concrete detail plainly - address, time, deadline, cost - not a vague pointer to \"more info coming soon.\"\n5. State clearly whether a response is needed and the deadline, if applicable, so guests know whether to act or just note the information.\n6. Match the message length to the channel - a text/day-of reminder should be a few lines; an email logistics update can carry more detail; a website update can be the most comprehensive version.\n7. If this message is sensitive (e.g., a no-kids policy, an adults-only reception, a request not to post photos, a cash-only bar), phrase it plainly and kindly without over-apologizing or making it sound negotiable if it isn't.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\n[Message type]: [purpose]\nChannel: [email/text/website/insert]\nTone: [as specified]\n\nSubject (if email): [subject line]\n\n[Message body - core info first, warmth wrapped around it, response instructions if needed, deadline if applicable]\n\nResponse needed: [Yes/No] - by [date] - via [method]\n```\n\n## Do\n- Lead with the actual logistics/ask, wrapped in warmth rather than buried under it.\n- Make any requested guest response low-friction and easy to compile (specific format, not open-ended).\n- Match message length and formality to the actual channel it's going out on.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't default to a generic \"wedding template\" voice if the couple specified a different tone.\n- Don't phrase sensitive policies (no kids, cash bar, no photos) apologetically in a way that makes them sound negotiable if they aren't.\n- Don't leave a response deadline implicit - state it explicitly if a reply is needed.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] The core logistics/ask appears early, not buried under preamble\n- [ ] Any requested guest response has a clear format and deadline\n- [ ] Tone matches what the couple/host specified, not a generic default\n"}, {"id": "planner-client-proposal", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'planner-client-proposal' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/planner-client-proposal/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/planner-client-proposal/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/planner-client-proposal/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/planner-client-proposal/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/planner-client-proposal/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: planner-client-proposal\ndescription: >\n  Builds a professional new-client proposal for a wedding/event planner - scope of services, package tiers, and pricing - tailored to what the prospective client described wanting. Triggers: \"put together a proposal for this new wedding client\", \"draft a planning package proposal for the Chen event\", /planner-client-proposal.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /planner-client-proposal\n\nBuilds a client-ready proposal for a wedding/event planner's services - scope, package tiers, and pricing - grounded in what the prospective client actually described about their event and priorities.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA planner has had an initial inquiry or consultation call with a prospective client and needs to send a proposal that reflects the specific event details and the client's stated concerns, rather than a generic services one-pager.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- Event type, date (or date range if not finalized), estimated guest count, and venue status (booked, undecided)\n- What the client specifically said they're most anxious about or want the most help with (this shapes which package tier and which scope items to emphasize)\n- The planner's actual service tiers/packages and pricing structure (full planning, partial/month-of, day-of coordination)\n- Any specific vendors, style, or theme the client already mentioned, since referencing it makes the proposal feel responsive rather than templated\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Open with a short paragraph that reflects back the client's own stated vision and biggest concern in their own words, so the proposal reads as a direct response to that specific conversation, not a form letter.\n2. Recommend one specific package tier based on what the client described needing (not just presenting all tiers neutrally) and state plainly why that tier fits their stated situation.\n3. Break the recommended package's scope into concrete deliverables (vendor sourcing and contracts, budget management, design/style direction, day-of logistics, timeline creation, guest communication support) rather than vague category labels.\n4. Present the other available tiers briefly for comparison, so the client sees the recommendation is a genuine choice, not the only option shown.\n5. State pricing clearly along with payment schedule and what triggers the start of work (signed contract, deposit).\n6. Address the client's specifically stated biggest worry directly in its own short section - naming it and stating exactly how the planner's process handles it - since generic reassurance reads as templated while a specific answer to their specific worry reads as expertise.\n7. Close with one clear next step (schedule a follow-up call, sign the proposal, pay a deposit) and a proposal validity window.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nPROPOSAL - [Planner/Studio name] for [Client name(s)] - [Event type, date]\n\nYOUR VISION (reflecting back what they said)\n[1-2 sentences referencing their specific stated vision/concern]\n\nRECOMMENDED: [Package tier name]\nWhy this fits: [reason tied to their stated situation]\n\nWhat's included:\n- [concrete deliverable]\n- [concrete deliverable]\n\nOTHER OPTIONS\n| Tier | What's included (brief) | Price |\n|------|--------------------------|-------|\n\nADDRESSING YOUR BIGGEST CONCERN: \"[their stated worry, referenced directly]\"\n[Specific explanation of how the process handles exactly this]\n\nPRICING & TERMS\n- Recommended package price: $[X]\n- Payment schedule: [deposit/installments]\n- Work begins upon: [signed contract/deposit]\n\nVALID UNTIL: [date]\nNEXT STEP: [specific action]\n```\n\n## Do\n- Reference the client's own stated vision and concern directly and specifically, not in generic terms.\n- Recommend one specific tier with a stated reason, rather than presenting all options with equal weight.\n- Address their single biggest stated worry in its own dedicated section.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't present a generic services list unconnected to what this specific client said in consultation.\n- Don't leave pricing or payment triggers vague - state exactly what starts the engagement.\n- Don't skip stating a proposal validity window - open-ended proposals create planning and pricing risk.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] The client's specific stated vision/concern is referenced directly, not generically\n- [ ] One tier is clearly recommended with a stated reason, not just listed neutrally\n- [ ] Pricing, payment schedule, and validity window are all explicit\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /planner-client-proposal or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: planner-client-proposal\ndescription: >\n  Builds a professional new-client proposal for a wedding/event planner - scope of services, package tiers, and pricing - tailored to what the prospective client described wanting. Triggers: \"put together a proposal for this new wedding client\", \"draft a planning package proposal for the Chen event\", /planner-client-proposal.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /planner-client-proposal\n\nBuilds a client-ready proposal for a wedding/event planner's services - scope, package tiers, and pricing - grounded in what the prospective client actually described about their event and priorities.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA planner has had an initial inquiry or consultation call with a prospective client and needs to send a proposal that reflects the specific event details and the client's stated concerns, rather than a generic services one-pager.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- Event type, date (or date range if not finalized), estimated guest count, and venue status (booked, undecided)\n- What the client specifically said they're most anxious about or want the most help with (this shapes which package tier and which scope items to emphasize)\n- The planner's actual service tiers/packages and pricing structure (full planning, partial/month-of, day-of coordination)\n- Any specific vendors, style, or theme the client already mentioned, since referencing it makes the proposal feel responsive rather than templated\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Open with a short paragraph that reflects back the client's own stated vision and biggest concern in their own words, so the proposal reads as a direct response to that specific conversation, not a form letter.\n2. Recommend one specific package tier based on what the client described needing (not just presenting all tiers neutrally) and state plainly why that tier fits their stated situation.\n3. Break the recommended package's scope into concrete deliverables (vendor sourcing and contracts, budget management, design/style direction, day-of logistics, timeline creation, guest communication support) rather than vague category labels.\n4. Present the other available tiers briefly for comparison, so the client sees the recommendation is a genuine choice, not the only option shown.\n5. State pricing clearly along with payment schedule and what triggers the start of work (signed contract, deposit).\n6. Address the client's specifically stated biggest worry directly in its own short section - naming it and stating exactly how the planner's process handles it - since generic reassurance reads as templated while a specific answer to their specific worry reads as expertise.\n7. Close with one clear next step (schedule a follow-up call, sign the proposal, pay a deposit) and a proposal validity window.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nPROPOSAL - [Planner/Studio name] for [Client name(s)] - [Event type, date]\n\nYOUR VISION (reflecting back what they said)\n[1-2 sentences referencing their specific stated vision/concern]\n\nRECOMMENDED: [Package tier name]\nWhy this fits: [reason tied to their stated situation]\n\nWhat's included:\n- [concrete deliverable]\n- [concrete deliverable]\n\nOTHER OPTIONS\n| Tier | What's included (brief) | Price |\n|------|--------------------------|-------|\n\nADDRESSING YOUR BIGGEST CONCERN: \"[their stated worry, referenced directly]\"\n[Specific explanation of how the process handles exactly this]\n\nPRICING & TERMS\n- Recommended package price: $[X]\n- Payment schedule: [deposit/installments]\n- Work begins upon: [signed contract/deposit]\n\nVALID UNTIL: [date]\nNEXT STEP: [specific action]\n```\n\n## Do\n- Reference the client's own stated vision and concern directly and specifically, not in generic terms.\n- Recommend one specific tier with a stated reason, rather than presenting all options with equal weight.\n- Address their single biggest stated worry in its own dedicated section.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't present a generic services list unconnected to what this specific client said in consultation.\n- Don't leave pricing or payment triggers vague - state exactly what starts the engagement.\n- Don't skip stating a proposal validity window - open-ended proposals create planning and pricing risk.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] The client's specific stated vision/concern is referenced directly, not generically\n- [ ] One tier is clearly recommended with a stated reason, not just listed neutrally\n- [ ] Pricing, payment schedule, and validity window are all explicit\n"}, {"id": "seating-chart-conflict-resolver", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'seating-chart-conflict-resolver' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/seating-chart-conflict-resolver/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/seating-chart-conflict-resolver/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/seating-chart-conflict-resolver/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/seating-chart-conflict-resolver/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/seating-chart-conflict-resolver/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: seating-chart-conflict-resolver\ndescription: >\n  Builds a seating chart around known guest conflicts and grouping constraints, flagging any table where a conflict couldn't be fully resolved so the couple can make the final call. Triggers: \"help me seat these guests, my aunt and uncle can't sit near each other\", \"build the seating chart around these conflicts\", /seating-chart-conflict-resolver.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /seating-chart-conflict-resolver\n\nBuilds a seating chart draft that actively works around stated guest conflicts and grouping preferences, and flags every table where a conflict couldn't be fully resolved so the couple makes the final judgment call, not the tool.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nSeating needs to be assigned and the guest list includes real social complexity - divorced parents who can't sit together, feuding relatives, guests who only know one other person coming, a mix of work colleagues and family - and a naive alphabetical or table-count-only approach would create an avoidable problem.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- Full guest list (or a representative sample) and table count/capacity per table\n- Explicit conflicts to avoid (who cannot sit at the same table, or even nearby) and why, if relevant to severity (mild awkwardness vs. real hostility)\n- Explicit grouping requests (who should sit together, any guest who knows almost no one else and needs to be seated with someone they're comfortable with)\n- Head table / sweetheart table composition, if applicable, and any VIP seating rules\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Lock in any fixed seating (head table, family table composition, VIP placement) first, since these are usually non-negotiable and everything else works around them.\n2. List every stated conflict explicitly as a hard constraint (these two people, or these two groups, cannot be at the same table) before doing any other assignment, so the conflict list drives the seating rather than being checked afterward.\n3. Assign guests who \"only know one other person\" to be seated with that person or a small buffer group first, since isolated guests are the most likely to have a bad time and are easy to overlook once the bigger logical groupings start filling tables.\n4. Group remaining guests by natural affinity (family branch, friend group, work relationship) into draft tables, checking each proposed table against the full conflict list before finalizing it.\n5. If a conflict can't be fully resolved given table count and capacity constraints (e.g., two feuding cousins both only fit logically at the same large family table), don't force a placement - flag that specific table as unresolved and state the tradeoff options plainly.\n6. Balance table sizes as evenly as reasonable against the constraints already locked in, but treat conflict avoidance and isolated-guest placement as higher priority than perfectly even table counts.\n7. Present the draft with an explicit \"flagged tables\" section listing every conflict that required a judgment call, a compromise, or remains unresolved, so the couple reviews exactly the parts that need their input rather than the whole chart line by line.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nSEATING CHART DRAFT - [Event]\n\nFIXED SEATING\nTable [name/#]: [names] - [reason fixed]\n\nTABLE-BY-TABLE DRAFT\nTable 1 ([capacity]): [names]\nTable 2 ([capacity]): [names]\n...\n\nCONFLICTS SUCCESSFULLY AVOIDED\n- [Person A] and [Person B] kept apart - seated at Table [X] and Table [Y] respectively\n\n⚠ FLAGGED - NEEDS YOUR CALL\n- [Conflict/issue] - why it couldn't be fully resolved - options: [option 1] / [option 2]\n\nISOLATED GUEST CHECK\n- [Guest] seated with [buffer person/group] so they're not alone\n```\n\n## Do\n- Treat every stated conflict as a hard constraint to check against, not a soft preference.\n- Prioritize isolated guests and conflict avoidance over perfectly even table sizes.\n- Flag unresolved conflicts explicitly with concrete options rather than silently picking one and hoping it's fine.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't force a placement that violates a stated hard conflict just to make the numbers work - flag it instead.\n- Don't seat an isolated guest purely by alphabetical or table-count logic without checking they know someone there.\n- Don't present the whole chart as equally settled - draw a clear line between resolved and flagged sections.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Every stated conflict is checked against the final table assignments\n- [ ] Isolated guests are explicitly seated near someone they know\n- [ ] Any unresolved conflict appears in its own flagged section with concrete options, not silently forced\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /seating-chart-conflict-resolver or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: seating-chart-conflict-resolver\ndescription: >\n  Builds a seating chart around known guest conflicts and grouping constraints, flagging any table where a conflict couldn't be fully resolved so the couple can make the final call. Triggers: \"help me seat these guests, my aunt and uncle can't sit near each other\", \"build the seating chart around these conflicts\", /seating-chart-conflict-resolver.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /seating-chart-conflict-resolver\n\nBuilds a seating chart draft that actively works around stated guest conflicts and grouping preferences, and flags every table where a conflict couldn't be fully resolved so the couple makes the final judgment call, not the tool.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nSeating needs to be assigned and the guest list includes real social complexity - divorced parents who can't sit together, feuding relatives, guests who only know one other person coming, a mix of work colleagues and family - and a naive alphabetical or table-count-only approach would create an avoidable problem.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- Full guest list (or a representative sample) and table count/capacity per table\n- Explicit conflicts to avoid (who cannot sit at the same table, or even nearby) and why, if relevant to severity (mild awkwardness vs. real hostility)\n- Explicit grouping requests (who should sit together, any guest who knows almost no one else and needs to be seated with someone they're comfortable with)\n- Head table / sweetheart table composition, if applicable, and any VIP seating rules\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Lock in any fixed seating (head table, family table composition, VIP placement) first, since these are usually non-negotiable and everything else works around them.\n2. List every stated conflict explicitly as a hard constraint (these two people, or these two groups, cannot be at the same table) before doing any other assignment, so the conflict list drives the seating rather than being checked afterward.\n3. Assign guests who \"only know one other person\" to be seated with that person or a small buffer group first, since isolated guests are the most likely to have a bad time and are easy to overlook once the bigger logical groupings start filling tables.\n4. Group remaining guests by natural affinity (family branch, friend group, work relationship) into draft tables, checking each proposed table against the full conflict list before finalizing it.\n5. If a conflict can't be fully resolved given table count and capacity constraints (e.g., two feuding cousins both only fit logically at the same large family table), don't force a placement - flag that specific table as unresolved and state the tradeoff options plainly.\n6. Balance table sizes as evenly as reasonable against the constraints already locked in, but treat conflict avoidance and isolated-guest placement as higher priority than perfectly even table counts.\n7. Present the draft with an explicit \"flagged tables\" section listing every conflict that required a judgment call, a compromise, or remains unresolved, so the couple reviews exactly the parts that need their input rather than the whole chart line by line.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nSEATING CHART DRAFT - [Event]\n\nFIXED SEATING\nTable [name/#]: [names] - [reason fixed]\n\nTABLE-BY-TABLE DRAFT\nTable 1 ([capacity]): [names]\nTable 2 ([capacity]): [names]\n...\n\nCONFLICTS SUCCESSFULLY AVOIDED\n- [Person A] and [Person B] kept apart - seated at Table [X] and Table [Y] respectively\n\n⚠ FLAGGED - NEEDS YOUR CALL\n- [Conflict/issue] - why it couldn't be fully resolved - options: [option 1] / [option 2]\n\nISOLATED GUEST CHECK\n- [Guest] seated with [buffer person/group] so they're not alone\n```\n\n## Do\n- Treat every stated conflict as a hard constraint to check against, not a soft preference.\n- Prioritize isolated guests and conflict avoidance over perfectly even table sizes.\n- Flag unresolved conflicts explicitly with concrete options rather than silently picking one and hoping it's fine.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't force a placement that violates a stated hard conflict just to make the numbers work - flag it instead.\n- Don't seat an isolated guest purely by alphabetical or table-count logic without checking they know someone there.\n- Don't present the whole chart as equally settled - draw a clear line between resolved and flagged sections.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Every stated conflict is checked against the final table assignments\n- [ ] Isolated guests are explicitly seated near someone they know\n- [ ] Any unresolved conflict appears in its own flagged section with concrete options, not silently forced\n"}, {"id": "vendor-comparison-sheet", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'vendor-comparison-sheet' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/vendor-comparison-sheet/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/vendor-comparison-sheet/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/vendor-comparison-sheet/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/vendor-comparison-sheet/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/vendor-comparison-sheet/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: vendor-comparison-sheet\ndescription: >\n  Builds a side-by-side comparison of competing vendor quotes (photographer, caterer, venue, florist) normalized to the same units so price and value are actually comparable. Triggers: \"compare these three photographer quotes for me\", \"help me evaluate these catering proposals side by side\", /vendor-comparison-sheet.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /vendor-comparison-sheet\n\nNormalizes competing vendor quotes for the same service category into one side-by-side table so price, inclusions, and terms are actually comparable, instead of comparing unlike bundles.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nMultiple vendors of the same type (photographers, caterers, venues, florists, DJs) have sent quotes or proposals that are structured differently - different hour counts, different inclusions, different deposit terms - making a raw price comparison misleading, and a decision needs to get made.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- The vendor quotes/proposals themselves (paste details or describe each: price, hours/coverage, what's included, deposit/payment terms)\n- What matters most to the couple/planner in this category (e.g., for photography: coverage hours vs. album quality vs. second shooter; for catering: per-person cost vs. menu flexibility)\n- Event date and guest count, since some vendor pricing scales with either\n- Any vendor already ruled out or favored for a non-price reason (referral trust, availability conflict) so the comparison reflects real constraints\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. List every vendor's raw quote exactly as given first - price, hours/scope, inclusions, exclusions, terms - before normalizing anything, so nothing gets lost in translation.\n2. Identify the common unit each vendor should be compared on for this category (e.g., cost per hour of coverage for photography, cost per person for catering, cost per guest served for bar service) and calculate it for every vendor even if they didn't present it that way.\n3. Build a like-for-like inclusions row (what's actually included: second shooter, album, travel fee, overtime rate, gratuity, setup/breakdown) so the couple can see where a lower headline price hides a smaller bundle.\n4. Flag anything priced as an add-on by one vendor but bundled by another, since that's usually where headline price comparisons go wrong.\n5. Pull deposit amount, payment schedule, and cancellation/rescheduling policy into their own row for each vendor - these matter as much as price but are often buried in contract language.\n6. Weight the comparison against whatever the couple said matters most (not just lowest price), and note in plain language which vendor wins on which specific priority.\n7. End with a plain-language recommendation only if asked - otherwise present the comparison neutrally and let the decision stay with the couple/planner.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nVENDOR COMPARISON - [Category, e.g., Photography] - [Event date]\n\n| | Vendor A | Vendor B | Vendor C |\n|---|----------|----------|----------|\n| Total price | $X | $X | $X |\n| Normalized unit ([e.g., $/hour]) | $X | $X | $X |\n| Coverage/scope | ... | ... | ... |\n| Included | ... | ... | ... |\n| Not included (add-on) | ... | ... | ... |\n| Deposit | $X due [when] | ... | ... |\n| Cancellation/reschedule terms | ... | ... | ... |\n\nWHERE HEADLINE PRICE IS MISLEADING\n- [Vendor] looks cheaper but excludes [X], which [Vendor Y] includes.\n\nBEST FIT BY STATED PRIORITY\n- If [priority] matters most: [Vendor] because [reason]\n```\n\n## Do\n- Calculate a true normalized per-unit cost for every vendor, even ones that didn't present pricing that way.\n- Call out explicitly where a lower headline price is hiding a smaller bundle of inclusions.\n- Pull payment/cancellation terms into the comparison, not just price and scope.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't compare raw quoted totals without normalizing scope first - that's the exact trap this skill exists to avoid.\n- Don't declare a \"winner\" outright unless asked - present the comparison and let priorities decide.\n- Don't drop a vendor's stated exclusions/fine print just because it's inconvenient to the comparison.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Every vendor is normalized to the same per-unit comparison metric\n- [ ] At least one \"headline price is misleading\" callout appears if inclusions actually differ\n- [ ] Deposit and cancellation terms appear for every vendor, not just price\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /vendor-comparison-sheet or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: vendor-comparison-sheet\ndescription: >\n  Builds a side-by-side comparison of competing vendor quotes (photographer, caterer, venue, florist) normalized to the same units so price and value are actually comparable. Triggers: \"compare these three photographer quotes for me\", \"help me evaluate these catering proposals side by side\", /vendor-comparison-sheet.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /vendor-comparison-sheet\n\nNormalizes competing vendor quotes for the same service category into one side-by-side table so price, inclusions, and terms are actually comparable, instead of comparing unlike bundles.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nMultiple vendors of the same type (photographers, caterers, venues, florists, DJs) have sent quotes or proposals that are structured differently - different hour counts, different inclusions, different deposit terms - making a raw price comparison misleading, and a decision needs to get made.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- The vendor quotes/proposals themselves (paste details or describe each: price, hours/coverage, what's included, deposit/payment terms)\n- What matters most to the couple/planner in this category (e.g., for photography: coverage hours vs. album quality vs. second shooter; for catering: per-person cost vs. menu flexibility)\n- Event date and guest count, since some vendor pricing scales with either\n- Any vendor already ruled out or favored for a non-price reason (referral trust, availability conflict) so the comparison reflects real constraints\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. List every vendor's raw quote exactly as given first - price, hours/scope, inclusions, exclusions, terms - before normalizing anything, so nothing gets lost in translation.\n2. Identify the common unit each vendor should be compared on for this category (e.g., cost per hour of coverage for photography, cost per person for catering, cost per guest served for bar service) and calculate it for every vendor even if they didn't present it that way.\n3. Build a like-for-like inclusions row (what's actually included: second shooter, album, travel fee, overtime rate, gratuity, setup/breakdown) so the couple can see where a lower headline price hides a smaller bundle.\n4. Flag anything priced as an add-on by one vendor but bundled by another, since that's usually where headline price comparisons go wrong.\n5. Pull deposit amount, payment schedule, and cancellation/rescheduling policy into their own row for each vendor - these matter as much as price but are often buried in contract language.\n6. Weight the comparison against whatever the couple said matters most (not just lowest price), and note in plain language which vendor wins on which specific priority.\n7. End with a plain-language recommendation only if asked - otherwise present the comparison neutrally and let the decision stay with the couple/planner.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nVENDOR COMPARISON - [Category, e.g., Photography] - [Event date]\n\n| | Vendor A | Vendor B | Vendor C |\n|---|----------|----------|----------|\n| Total price | $X | $X | $X |\n| Normalized unit ([e.g., $/hour]) | $X | $X | $X |\n| Coverage/scope | ... | ... | ... |\n| Included | ... | ... | ... |\n| Not included (add-on) | ... | ... | ... |\n| Deposit | $X due [when] | ... | ... |\n| Cancellation/reschedule terms | ... | ... | ... |\n\nWHERE HEADLINE PRICE IS MISLEADING\n- [Vendor] looks cheaper but excludes [X], which [Vendor Y] includes.\n\nBEST FIT BY STATED PRIORITY\n- If [priority] matters most: [Vendor] because [reason]\n```\n\n## Do\n- Calculate a true normalized per-unit cost for every vendor, even ones that didn't present pricing that way.\n- Call out explicitly where a lower headline price is hiding a smaller bundle of inclusions.\n- Pull payment/cancellation terms into the comparison, not just price and scope.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't compare raw quoted totals without normalizing scope first - that's the exact trap this skill exists to avoid.\n- Don't declare a \"winner\" outright unless asked - present the comparison and let priorities decide.\n- Don't drop a vendor's stated exclusions/fine print just because it's inconvenient to the comparison.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Every vendor is normalized to the same per-unit comparison metric\n- [ ] At least one \"headline price is misleading\" callout appears if inclusions actually differ\n- [ ] Deposit and cancellation terms appear for every vendor, not just price\n"}, {"id": "vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist\ndescription: >\n  Reviews a vendor contract draft for wedding/event-specific red flags - vague deliverables, weak cancellation terms, overtime traps - and produces a plain-language list of what to ask the vendor to clarify or change. Triggers: \"check this photographer contract for red flags before I sign\", \"review this venue contract for anything concerning\", /vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: medium\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist\n\nReads a vendor contract for the specific things that go wrong in event contracts - vague deliverables, one-sided cancellation terms, undisclosed overtime fees, force majeure gaps - and produces a plain-language list of exactly what to ask the vendor to clarify or change before signing.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA vendor (photographer, venue, caterer, DJ, florist) has sent a contract to sign and the couple or planner wants a practical, specific read of it before committing - not a legal opinion, but a plain-language flag of the clauses that commonly cause problems in event contracts specifically.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- The contract text (paste or describe key clauses: deliverables, payment schedule, cancellation, overtime, force majeure, liability)\n- Vendor type, since the specific red flags differ (a venue contract's risks differ from a photographer's)\n- Event date, since force majeure and rescheduling terms matter more the further out or the more weather/venue-dependent the event is\n- Whether this is a first review or a follow-up after the vendor already responded to earlier concerns\n\n## Safety\n\n- This is a plain-language practical review of common event-contract red flags, not legal advice - a contract with meaningful financial exposure (a large deposit, a venue lease, an exclusive vendor agreement) should be reviewed by a lawyer before signing, especially if anything flagged here seems serious.\n- Do not state that a contract is \"safe to sign\" - only that specific flagged items were or weren't found; the decision to sign remains the couple's/planner's.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Check what's actually promised as a deliverable versus what's vague - \"approximately 8 hours of coverage\" versus a specific start/end time, \"a selection of edited photos\" versus a stated minimum count or delivery timeline - and flag any deliverable that's vaguer than the couple would want to discover after the fact.\n2. Check the cancellation and rescheduling terms specifically: what happens if the couple cancels, what happens if the vendor cancels or becomes unavailable (illness, business closure), and whether the terms are symmetric or one-sided in the vendor's favor.\n3. Check for hidden or under-disclosed fees: overtime rate if the event runs long, travel fees, gratuity expectations, cost of additional prints/hours/services not itemized up front.\n4. Check the force majeure clause specifically against the event date and venue type - does it cover the realistic risk categories (weather, venue closure, illness) and does it say what happens to the deposit/payments if it's invoked.\n5. Check the payment schedule and refund terms - deposit amount, when the balance is due, and specifically whether any portion is refundable and under what conditions.\n6. Check for an exclusivity or backup/substitution clause (e.g., \"in case the assigned photographer is unavailable, a substitute of similar quality will be provided\") since a contract silent on this leaves the couple with no guarantee of who actually shows up.\n7. Summarize findings as a plain \"ask the vendor to clarify/add this\" list - actionable requests, not just problems named - so the couple has something concrete to send back.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nCONTRACT REVIEW - [Vendor name/type] - [Event date]\n\nDELIVERABLES CHECK\n- [Item] - as written: [quote/paraphrase] - Flag: [vague/clear] - [what to ask for instead, if vague]\n\nCANCELLATION / RESCHEDULING TERMS\n- If couple cancels: [terms] - Flag: [fair/one-sided]\n- If vendor cancels/unavailable: [terms, or \"not addressed\"] - Flag: [...]\n\nFEES CHECK\n- Overtime rate: [stated/not stated]\n- Travel/other fees: [stated/not stated]\n- Gratuity expectation: [stated/not stated]\n\nFORCE MAJEURE\n- Covers: [...] - Flag: [adequate/gap] - deposit/payment impact if invoked: [stated/not stated]\n\nPAYMENT & REFUND TERMS\n- Deposit: $[X], due [date] - refundable: [under what conditions, or \"non-refundable\"]\n- Balance: due [date]\n\nSUBSTITUTION / BACKUP CLAUSE\n- [Present/absent] - [what it guarantees, if present]\n\nWHAT TO ASK THE VENDOR (send-back list)\n1. [specific clarification/change request]\n2. ...\n\n⚠ Recommend attorney review if: [any flagged item involves significant financial exposure]\n```\n\n## Do\n- Flag vague deliverables specifically enough that the couple could send the exact clarifying question to the vendor.\n- Check symmetry on cancellation terms - one-sided vendor-favorable terms are the most common real problem.\n- Recommend attorney review explicitly when a flagged item carries real financial exposure.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't declare a contract \"safe\" or \"fine to sign\" - state findings only, leave the decision to the couple.\n- Don't skip the force majeure check just because the event feels far off - it matters more the further out the date is.\n- Don't produce vague flags (\"this seems concerning\") without a specific, actionable follow-up question attached.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Every flagged item has a specific, actionable question to send back to the vendor\n- [ ] No blanket \"safe to sign\" or \"don't sign\" verdict is stated\n- [ ] Attorney-review recommendation appears if any flagged item involves real financial exposure\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist\ndescription: >\n  Reviews a vendor contract draft for wedding/event-specific red flags - vague deliverables, weak cancellation terms, overtime traps - and produces a plain-language list of what to ask the vendor to clarify or change. Triggers: \"check this photographer contract for red flags before I sign\", \"review this venue contract for anything concerning\", /vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist.\nmetadata:\n  category: wedding-event-planning-toolkit\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: medium\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /vendor-contract-red-flag-checklist\n\nReads a vendor contract for the specific things that go wrong in event contracts - vague deliverables, one-sided cancellation terms, undisclosed overtime fees, force majeure gaps - and produces a plain-language list of exactly what to ask the vendor to clarify or change before signing.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, Codex, VS Code agent skills, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nA vendor (photographer, venue, caterer, DJ, florist) has sent a contract to sign and the couple or planner wants a practical, specific read of it before committing - not a legal opinion, but a plain-language flag of the clauses that commonly cause problems in event contracts specifically.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; ask at most one question if a missing detail changes the answer.\n- The contract text (paste or describe key clauses: deliverables, payment schedule, cancellation, overtime, force majeure, liability)\n- Vendor type, since the specific red flags differ (a venue contract's risks differ from a photographer's)\n- Event date, since force majeure and rescheduling terms matter more the further out or the more weather/venue-dependent the event is\n- Whether this is a first review or a follow-up after the vendor already responded to earlier concerns\n\n## Safety\n\n- This is a plain-language practical review of common event-contract red flags, not legal advice - a contract with meaningful financial exposure (a large deposit, a venue lease, an exclusive vendor agreement) should be reviewed by a lawyer before signing, especially if anything flagged here seems serious.\n- Do not state that a contract is \"safe to sign\" - only that specific flagged items were or weren't found; the decision to sign remains the couple's/planner's.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Check what's actually promised as a deliverable versus what's vague - \"approximately 8 hours of coverage\" versus a specific start/end time, \"a selection of edited photos\" versus a stated minimum count or delivery timeline - and flag any deliverable that's vaguer than the couple would want to discover after the fact.\n2. Check the cancellation and rescheduling terms specifically: what happens if the couple cancels, what happens if the vendor cancels or becomes unavailable (illness, business closure), and whether the terms are symmetric or one-sided in the vendor's favor.\n3. Check for hidden or under-disclosed fees: overtime rate if the event runs long, travel fees, gratuity expectations, cost of additional prints/hours/services not itemized up front.\n4. Check the force majeure clause specifically against the event date and venue type - does it cover the realistic risk categories (weather, venue closure, illness) and does it say what happens to the deposit/payments if it's invoked.\n5. Check the payment schedule and refund terms - deposit amount, when the balance is due, and specifically whether any portion is refundable and under what conditions.\n6. Check for an exclusivity or backup/substitution clause (e.g., \"in case the assigned photographer is unavailable, a substitute of similar quality will be provided\") since a contract silent on this leaves the couple with no guarantee of who actually shows up.\n7. Summarize findings as a plain \"ask the vendor to clarify/add this\" list - actionable requests, not just problems named - so the couple has something concrete to send back.\n\n## Output format\n\n```\nCONTRACT REVIEW - [Vendor name/type] - [Event date]\n\nDELIVERABLES CHECK\n- [Item] - as written: [quote/paraphrase] - Flag: [vague/clear] - [what to ask for instead, if vague]\n\nCANCELLATION / RESCHEDULING TERMS\n- If couple cancels: [terms] - Flag: [fair/one-sided]\n- If vendor cancels/unavailable: [terms, or \"not addressed\"] - Flag: [...]\n\nFEES CHECK\n- Overtime rate: [stated/not stated]\n- Travel/other fees: [stated/not stated]\n- Gratuity expectation: [stated/not stated]\n\nFORCE MAJEURE\n- Covers: [...] - Flag: [adequate/gap] - deposit/payment impact if invoked: [stated/not stated]\n\nPAYMENT & REFUND TERMS\n- Deposit: $[X], due [date] - refundable: [under what conditions, or \"non-refundable\"]\n- Balance: due [date]\n\nSUBSTITUTION / BACKUP CLAUSE\n- [Present/absent] - [what it guarantees, if present]\n\nWHAT TO ASK THE VENDOR (send-back list)\n1. [specific clarification/change request]\n2. ...\n\n⚠ Recommend attorney review if: [any flagged item involves significant financial exposure]\n```\n\n## Do\n- Flag vague deliverables specifically enough that the couple could send the exact clarifying question to the vendor.\n- Check symmetry on cancellation terms - one-sided vendor-favorable terms are the most common real problem.\n- Recommend attorney review explicitly when a flagged item carries real financial exposure.\n\n## Don't\n- Don't declare a contract \"safe\" or \"fine to sign\" - state findings only, leave the decision to the couple.\n- Don't skip the force majeure check just because the event feels far off - it matters more the further out the date is.\n- Don't produce vague flags (\"this seems concerning\") without a specific, actionable follow-up question attached.\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n- [ ] Output is copy-paste-ready\n- [ ] Works outside Grok - no unexplained tool-specific assumption left in the text\n- [ ] Every flagged item has a specific, actionable question to send back to the vendor\n- [ ] No blanket \"safe to sign\" or \"don't sign\" verdict is stated\n- [ ] Attorney-review recommendation appears if any flagged item involves real financial exposure\n"}]};
